		{"id":"e27d900accd1ef95","type":"text","text":"# old shit","x":-3800,"y":-798,"width":150,"height":60},
		{"id":"6968a814f8950b3d","type":"text","text":"# Components\nThe creature's actual components will allow the creature to perform actions and movement to complete their goals\n- HealthComponent\n- NutritionComponent\n- MovementComponent\n- EyeComponent\n...to name a few","x":-2690,"y":-974,"width":320,"height":284},
		{"id":"d36d35cbc08b8f5d","type":"text","text":"# StateComponent\n(presentation)\nHow the creature appears while acting\n","x":-2690,"y":-586,"width":400,"height":236},
		{"id":"0f4cf88f942bc817","type":"text","text":"# GoalComponent\n(decision-making)\nONLY describes intent\n```gdscript\nvar goal: Dictionary = {\n\t\"direction\": Vector2,\n\t\"action\": String,\n\t\"target\", Node2D\n}\n```\n\nEach goal has a custom `evaluate_priority()` function which is called every frame.\nNaturally, each goal also has a priority which influences when it will be picked from a brain's stack of goals.\nGoals can be split into basic want modules:\n- I want food\n- I want safety\n- I want treasure\netc.\n","x":-3250,"y":-852,"width":400,"height":500},
		{"id":"8ec62334c73e9710","type":"text","text":"# BrainModule\nKeeps a stack of GoalComponents, organizes and calls their functions to give creatures a goal.\nEncourages emergent behavior using the priority-based goal system and personality parameters.","x":-3800,"y":-690,"width":430,"height":176},
		{"id":"ced146fe3fd821bb","type":"text","text":"```gdscript\nclass_name Brain\nextends Node\n\nsignal intent_changed(old_intent: Intent, new_intent: Intent)\nsignal goal_changed(old_goal_name: String, new_goal_name: String, new_priority: float)\n\n@export var creature: Node2D\n\n@export var personality: Dictionary[String, float] = {\n\t\"aggression\": 0.0,\n\t\"bravery\": 0.0,\n\t\"dominance\": 0.0,\n\t\"energy\": 0.0,\n\t\"nervous\": 0.0,\n\t\"sympathy\": 0.0\n}\n\n# goal management\nvar goals: Array[Goal] = []\nvar current_intent: Intent = null\nvar current_goal: Goal = null\n\n# memory system for persistent state\nvar memory: Dictionary = {}\n\n@export var priority_threshold: float = 1.2 # new goal must be this much higher to switch\n@export var min_goal_durations: float = 0.1 # minimum time before switching goals\n\nvar time_since_goal_change: float = 0.0\n\nfunc _ready() -> void:\n\tdetermine_personality()\n\t_gather_goals()\n\t\n\tcurrent_intent = Intent.new()\n\tcurrent_intent.action = \"idle\"\n\t\nfunc _process(delta: float) -> void:\n\ttime_since_goal_change += delta\n\t\n\tvar best_goal: Goal = _evaluate_goals()\n\t\n\tif _should_switch_goal(best_goal):\n\t\t_switch_to_goal(best_goal)\n\t\nfunc _gather_goals() -> void:\n\tgoals.clear()\n\tfor child in get_children():\n\t\tif child is Goal:\n\t\t\tgoals.append(child)\n\t\t\t\n\tif goals.is_empty():\n\t\tpush_warning(\"[Brain] No goals found for creature: %s\" % creature.name)\n\t\t\n\nfunc _evaluate_goals() -> Goal:\n\tvar best_goal: Goal = null\n\tvar highest_priority: float = -INF\n\t\n\tfor goal in goals:\n\t\tvar evaluated_priority = goal.evaluate_priority(self)\n\t\t\n\t\tif evaluated_priority > highest_priority:\n\t\t\thighest_priority = evaluated_priority\n\t\t\tbest_goal = goal\n\t\t\t\n\treturn best_goal\n\t\nfunc _should_switch_goal(new_goal: Goal) -> bool:\n\tif current_goal == null:\n\t\treturn new_goal != null\n\t\t\n\tif new_goal == null:\n\t\treturn false\n\t\t\n\tif new_goal == current_goal:\n\t\treturn false\n\t\t\n\tif time_since_goal_change < min_goal_duration:\n\t\treturn false\n\t\t\n\tvar current_priority = current_goal.evaluate_priority(self)\n\tvar new_priority = new_goal.evaluate_priority(self)\n\t\n\t# only switch if new goal is significantly better\n\treturn new_priority > current_priority + priority_threshold\n\t\n\t\nfunc _switch_to_goal(new_goal: Goal) -> void:\n\tvar old_intent = current_intent\n\tvar old_goal_name = current_goal.name if current_goal else \"none\"\n\t\n\tcurrent_goal = new_goal\n\ttime_since_goal_change = 0.0\n\t\n\tif new_goal == null:\n\t\tcurrent_intent = Intent.new()\n\t\tcurrent_intent.action = \"idle\"\n\t\tcurrent_intent.goal_name = \"idle\"\n\telse:\n\t\tcurrent_intent = new_goal.generate_intent(self)\n\t\tcurrent_intent.goal_name = new_goal.name\n\t\tcurrent_intent.priority = new_goal.evaluate_priority(self)\n\t\t\n\tgoal_changed.emit(old_goal_name, current_intent.goal_name, current_intent.priority)\n\tintent_changed.emit(old_intent, current_intent)\n\t\nfunc get_current_intent() -> Intent:\n\treturn current_intent\n\t\nfunc force_reevaluate() -> void:\n\tvar best_goal = _evaluate_goals()\n\tvar old_threshold = priority_threshold\n\tpriority_threshold = -INF\n\tif _should_switch_goal(best_goal):\n\t\t_switch_to_goal(best_goal)\n\tpriority_threshold = old_threshold\n\t\nfunc determine_personality() -> void:\n\tpersonality[\"aggression\"] = randf()\n\tpersonality[\"bravery\"] = randf()\n\tpersonality[\"dominance\"] = randf()\n\tpersonality[\"energy\"] = randf()\n\tpersonality[\"nervous\"] = randf()\n\tpersonality[\"sympathy\"] = randf()\n\t\nfunc remember(key: String, value: Variant) -> void:\n\tmemory[key] = value\n\t\nfunc recall(key: String, default = null) -> Variant:\n\treturn memory.get(key, default)\n\t\nfunc forget(key: String) -> void:\n\tmemory.erase(key)\n\t\nfunc has_memory(key: String) -> bool:\n\treturn memory.has(key)\n\t\nfunc clear_memory() -> void:\n\tmemory.clear()\n\t\nfunc get_memory_keys() -> Array:\n\treturn memory.keys()\n\n\n```","x":-3510,"y":-314,"width":360,"height":193},
		{"id":"b559218e16ff74f8","type":"text","text":"# IntentExecutor (ver1)\n```gdscript\nclass_name IntentExecutor\nextends Node\n\n@export var creature: Node2D\nvar current_intent: CreatureIntent\nvar action_handlers: Dictionary = {} # String -> Callable\n\n￼func _ready():\n\t# register built-in handlers\n\t_register_default_handlers()\n\t\n\t# allow components to register their own handlers\n\t_discover_component_handlers() \n\t\n\n\tvar brain = creature.get_node_or_null(\"BrainComponent\")\n\t￼if brain:\n\t\tbrain.intent_changed.connect(_on_intent_changed)\n\t\t\n\t\t\n￼func _register_default_handlers():\n\t# register common action patterns\n\tregister_action(\"idle\", _handle_idle)\n\tregister_action(\"move_to\", _handle_move_to)\n\tregister_action(\"wander\", _handle_wander)\n\tregister_action(\"flee\", _handle_flee)\n\tregister_action(\"follow\", _handle_follow)\n\t\n￼func _discover_component_handlers():\n\t# let components register their own action handlers\n\tfor child in creature.get_children()\n\tif child.has_method(\"register_intent_handlers\"):\n\t\tchild.register_intent_handlers(self)==-\n\t\t\nfunc register_action(action_name: String, handler: Callable):\n\t# public api for components to register handlers\n\taction_handlers[action_name] = handler\t\t\n\t\t\nfunc _on_intent_changed(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tcurrent_intent = intent\n\t_execute_intent(intent)\n\t\n\t\nfunc _execute_intent(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tif intent.target_position != Vector2.ZERO or intent.target_entity != null:\n\t\t_handle_movement_to_target(intent)\n\t\t\n\tif intent.look_target != null:\n\t\t_handle_gaze(intent)\n\t\t\n\tif action_handlers.has(intent.action):\n\t\taction_handlers[intent.action].call(intent)\n\telse:\n\t\t_try_component_dispatch(intent)\n\t\t\nfunc _try_component_dispatch(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\t# try to find a component that can handle this action\n\tfor child in creature.get_children():\n\t\tif child.has_method(\"handle_intent\"):\n\t\t\tif child.handle_intent(intent):\n\t\t\t\treturn # component handled it\n\t\n# these default methods should probably not be in the intent executor, they should be in the components themselves, dummy\nfunc _handle_movement_to_target(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n\t\nfunc _handle_gaze(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n\t\nfunc _handle_idle(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n\t\nfunc _handle_move_to(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n\t\nfunc _handle_wander(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n\t\nfunc _handle_flee(intent: CreatureIntent):\n\tpass\n```","x":-3130,"y":-292,"width":300,"height":150,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"a981ba3c89b61f15","type":"text","text":"line of sight vision system\n\nAll entities have some sort of signifier attached to them.\n\nA mask is placed on top of the game world; all entities underneath the mask are occluded. There should be support for exceptions in the case of special entities or events. The mask should show the game world but occlude entities. The mask should support any color with any transparency.\n\nThe player has special awareness so a shape will be cut out of the mask. This shape should be a circle; fully opaque in the middle with a smooth transition to full transparency on the outside.\n\nThis way, the player cuts a hole into the mask.\n\nThe tricky part is figuring out how to render partially occluded entities. Entities out of line of sight should not be rendered; entities on the edge of line of sight (partial transparency of the mask) should also be partially rendered.","x":-45,"y":-3366,"width":439,"height":746},
		{"id":"9bb10bc01d8579b5","type":"text","text":"Protect dreamland as Seth, the tenacious curator of the Anthurium. A curse has fell over dreamland, spreading a dark and gruesome fog. Protect and feed the legendary Anthurium plant, which holds a secret in expelling the mysterious fog.\n\nFight, befriend, or utilize the wacky creatures native to dreamland to accomplish your goal and last as many days as you can under worsening circumstances.\n\nYou play as Seth, a creature gifted with free will and the ability to manipulate the world around you! Pick up and throw objects, use items, and create new ways to survive and thrive in a cursed dreamland.\n\nSimilar games might include: forget-me-not, link's awakening, rain world, kirby.","x":415,"y":-3366,"width":510,"height":860},
		{"id":"85e6fad56aab6285","type":"text","text":"Terrain states?\n\nGround:\n- walkable\n- texture\n- movement slow?\n- friction loss?\n- unidirectional?\n- apply velocity?\n- allow slip? (in case of gap vicinity)\n- damage on contact?\n\nWall:\n- collision\n- texture\n- only walkable to specific creatures\n\nGap:\n- fall\n- sometimes texture\n- transport after fall?\n- kill after fall?\n- damage after fall?\n\nthe goal is to be able to procedurally generate terrain so that a map is generated at the start of the game.\n\nadditionally, it should be possible to change terrain types midgame and have adjacent tiles change their texture to tile when necessary.","x":935,"y":-3366,"width":399,"height":840},
		{"id":"33fd299476486ce8","type":"text","text":"the anthurium plant\n\nLives in the center of the map as a massive rooted entity. The Anthurium plant can be harmed directly but is quite capable of defending itself. It is susceptible to environmental changes. The Anthurium has complex AI to make it seem ravenous, alien, intelligent, and powerful.\n\nThe Anthurium produces a pheromone which blows the **fog** away and ensnares any **grues** left during the daytime. The flower blooms during the day and closes during dusk, which causes the fog to slowly roll in.\n\nThe player is the plant's curator; ensuring its survival among the chaos of the dream arena. Although the plant is quite strong and capable of defending itself, the main way the player loses the game is if the flower dies.\n\nThe Anthurium can be fed different items to get powerful artifacts.\n\nThe Anthurium has different parts which interact with things in different ways. It can grow any of these parts at will depending on the conditions in the arena.\n- **Roots** are dense and durable walls.\n- **Thorns** are weak walls but can deal contact damage.\n- **Snares** can grow below creatures and root them in place.\n- **Pitchers** grow occasionally and can eat creatures or items\n\nAny of the Anthurium's parts act as sensors for the whole plant. Any activity that happens around these parts are known by the flower.\n\nThe Anthurium can create shards of concentrated creature energy so that you may use the abilities of other creatures.\n\n> Perhaps the Anthurium can mutate depending on what it eats? Or if it eats poisoned or unique or esoteric material it transforms?\n> Maybe the Anthurium can be corrupted and spread too much, causing harm to the environment, like an invasive plant.\n\n> The Anthurium could influence the environment and change its properties.\n\nEarly morning\n- Anthurium wakes up, fills up a small radius of pheromone providing a smaller safe area around the flower.\n\nDaybreak\n- Anthurium blooms and blows the fog away in a radius dependent on its health (healthier flower means more places to explore)\n\nDay\n- Anthurium reacts to events in the dream dungeon, may spread depending on conditions.\n- The player is most likely to feed the flower during this phase\n\nSunset\n- Race back to the flower as the fog begins to roll in.\n- The Anthurium's spathe begins to glow orange. If the flower is still hungry, it will begin to actively spread its roots widely to search for food. This can include the player.\n\nNight\n- The fog rolls in completely, and grues roam the land killing all creatures who remain outside.\n- The player should return to their den immediately if they can survive the grues.\n\n","x":1355,"y":-3366,"width":540,"height":1340},
		{"id":"b9c383c6e0bac3f9","type":"text","text":"prototype anthurium\n\nA great alien plant lives in the center of the game world. It is your job to curate it and ensure its survival, as it is the only thing keeping the world at bay from the gruesome fog.\n\nAnthurium cycles\nDay:\n\tBloom at the beginning of the day, allowing creatures to come out and fight or explore.\n\nDusk:\n\tGlow orange and the fog begins to slowly pull in. Creatures look for places to sleep.\n\nNight:\n\tFlower recedes and the fog descends fully. Grues come out in full force, capturing or killing any creatures left out.\n\nAnthurium Pitcher\nAccepts food of all types, grants the player points when accepted.\nThe plant has a requirement for the day:\n1) 10\n2) 15\n3) 20\n4) 25\n5) 30\n\nAny foods turned in past this maximum grants extra points. If the day ends and the plant has had less than the requirement then the next day starts with less time.","x":1915,"y":-3366,"width":620,"height":820},
		{"id":"1ac5eb742b54b5f6","type":"text","text":"resume\n\nProject Experience\n\nNotes App 3/17/2023\n- User interface\n- Special features\n- Experience with .NET API\n- Binary serialization, saving/loading files\n\nMP3 Player 3/3/2024\n- Python skills\n- User interface\n- Wrote custom UI using python packages\n\nCarmine's Retribution 5/6/2024\n- Understanding of rendering\n- Skill in pixel art and animation\n- Game design (arcade)\n- Git and GitHub and better commit messages\n\nSIC/XE Code Assembler 12/18/2024\n- Understanding of low-level computer systems\n\nNail It! 12/8/2025\n- Proficiency in C# and Unity\n- Composition based architecture\n- Level design\n- Smooth camera controls\n- Understanding of motion, interpolation, and vector math\n\nPortfolio Site 12/8/2025\n- Proficiency in basic HTML and CSS\n- Understanding of basic yet effective website theming and layout\n- Visual Studio Code\n\nAnthurium (ongoing)\n- Composition over inheritance\n- Scripting\n- Experimenting in OpenGL\n- Godot","x":-745,"y":-3386,"width":585,"height":973},
		{"id":"94c740497e9cb43d","type":"text","text":"game variables\n\n```gdscript\n# manage time of day\nvar time: float = 0.0\nenum TimeState{DAWN, DAY, DUSK, NIGHT}\nvar time_state: TimeState = TimeState.DAWN\n\n\n# for gui purposes, rendering player stats\nvar player_stats: EntityStatistics\n\n```\n\nhow should i manage systems in one place? especially objects/entities that have special effects?\n\nthis is a component-driven system, so it seems odd to go with one component to manage the whole game.\n\nright now, i need these components:\n- UIComponent\n- TimeComponent\n- EntityManager\n- WeatherManager\n- CameraController\n\nat this stage in development, i'm trying to control the radius of fog, always keep the center focused on the Anthurium plant (an entity in the YSort node), and on the initial spawn of the plant, the WorldGrid should create ground cells around the plant.\n\nhow do i manage special conditions over multiple components? should i have a unifying gamemanager?\n\nso far my project is laid out like this:\n```\nMain\n├── GameManager\n├── DungeonGenerator\n├── CameraController\n├── UI\n└── SubViewportContainer\n\t└── SubViewport\n\t\t└── Container\n\t\t\t├── Camera\n\t\t\t└── World\n\t\t\t\t├── WorldRenderer\n\t\t\t\t├── Weather\n\t\t\t\t├── YSort\n\t\t\t\t└── BG\n```\n\ni think that a refactor would be useful.\n\nlet's come up with a couple scenarios that would need to be handled by some system.\n\n```\n\n- anthurium plant spawns in\n- the worldgrid is altered to create ground tiles around the plant\n\n- player tosses a fruit into an Anthurium pitcher and the fruit is accepted by the pitcher\n- the player gains points\n\t- render this as a numeric particle\n\t- also change some ui\n\n- player spawns in\n- camera begins to follow them\n\n- player gets near the anthurium plant\n- some dialogue pops in\n\n- every 15 seconds, decide to spawn another entity or not\\\n\t- point system?\n- spawn an entity if decision is yes\n\n- the player dies, a game over\n- after some time, the camera begins following a random creature\n- after some time, ui shows up displaying options\n  \n```","x":-1520,"y":-3386,"width":745,"height":1546},
		{"id":"30c5a992a8fa6d65","x":832,"y":-5400,"width":605,"height":1966,"type":"text","text":"one issue that i'm running into right now is that I have a singleton WorldGrid that has this method:\n\n```gdscript\nfunc set_cell(coords: Vector2i, data: CellData) -> void:\n\tif not _in_bounds(coords):\n\t\treturn\n\t_grid[_idx(coords)] = data\n\tcell_changed.emit(coords)\n\tprint(\"cell_changed emiited\")\n```\n\nand the WorldRenderer looks like this:\n\n```gdscript\nextends TileMapLayer\nclass_name WorldRenderer\n\nconst TERRAIN_ATLAS: Dictionary = {\n\tCellData.TerrainType.GROUND: Vector2i(0, 0),\n\tCellData.TerrainType.WALL: Vector2i(1, 0),\n\tCellData.TerrainType.GAP: Vector2i(2, 0),\n}\n\nconst ATLAS_SOURCE_ID = 0\n\nfunc _ready() -> void:\n\tWorldGrid.cell_changed.connect(_on_cell_changed)\n\t\nfunc _on_cell_changed(coords: Vector2i) -> void:\n\t_draw_cell(coords)\n\t\nfunc _draw_cell(coords: Vector2i) -> void:\n\tvar cell = WorldGrid.get_cell(coords)\n\tif not cell:\n\t\treturn\n\t\t\n\tvar atlas_coords = TERRAIN_ATLAS.get(cell.terrain, Vector2i(0, 0))\n\tset_cell(coords, ATLAS_SOURCE_ID, atlas_coords)\n\t\nfunc render_all() -> void:\n\tfor y in WorldGrid.height:\n\t\tfor x in WorldGrid.width:\n\t\t\tvar coords = Vector2i(x, y)\n\t\t\t_draw_cell(coords)\n\t\t\t\n```\n\nand my GameManager right now looks like this:\n\n```gdscript\nextends Node\nclass_name GameManager\n\n\nstatic var _entity_container: Node2D\nstatic var player: CharacterBody2D\nstatic var time: float = 0.0\n\n@export var camera_controller: CameraController\n@export var ysort: Node2D\n@export var world: Node2D\n@export var weather: WeatherComponent\n@export var anthurium: Node2D\n@export var world_renderer: WorldRenderer\n\n@export var dungeon_generator: DungeonGenerator\n\n@export var wgi: WorldGridInterface\n\nfunc _ready() -> void:\n\tif ysort:\n\t\t_entity_container = ysort\n\t\t\n\tWorldGrid.init_grid(64, 64)\n\tdungeon_generator.generate(1234)\n\t\n\t\n\tvar cell = CellData.new()\n\tcell.terrain = CellData.TerrainType.GROUND\n\tWorldGrid.set_cells(Vector2(0,0), Vector2(16, 16), cell)\n\t\n```\n\nso when i call methods like `generate()` and `WorldGrid.set_cells` which both invoke `WorldGrid.set_cell()` which emits that signal, i would think that `_on_cell_changed()` would be called, but it is not. maybe this is some weird godot loading trickery? i know that nodes deeper in the tree are loaded first, with the roots being loaded last. i know that `render_all()` exists, but i obviously need this signal to work properly if i'm to change terrain during runtime.\n\napparently the issue is load order, yes. i just need to do this in my GameManager:\n\n```gdscript\nfunc _ready() -> void:\n\tif ysort:\n\t\t_entity_container = ysort\n\t\t\n\tWorldGrid.init_grid(64, 64)\n\tcall_deferred(\"_start_generation\") # important, so that WorldGrid loads fully\n\t\nfunc _start_generation() -> void:\n\tdungeon_generator.generate(1234)\n\t\n\t\n\tvar cell = CellData.new()\n\tcell.terrain = CellData.TerrainType.GROUND\n\tWorldGrid.set_cells(Vector2(0,0), Vector2(16, 16), cell)\n```"}
	],
